			<ns0:name>cbiffle@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/cbiffle@google.com/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">eaeltsin suggested (in IM) adding comments to the sel_ldr, so that when we list the code that took the signal the documentation is inline.  This seems easy to do and helpful.

I'm suspicious of teaching the sel_ldr to notice gdb and change its behavior.  What if I were trying to debug this code?  This is only an issue for people who are debugging the trusted codebase -- the GDB RSP provides an illusion of only seeing untrusted code and will not be affected.  So I think the correct long-term fix is simply documentation.  (Unless someone can come up with a better way to test execution of data, without requiring a signal.)</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-11-02T17:05:09.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-11-02T17:05:09.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates>
